SIMPLE: licentiate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Licentiate
<hw>Li*cen"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(l⟦isl⟧*s⟦ecr⟧n"sh⟦icr⟧*⟦asl⟧t ⟦or⟧
-sh⟦asl⟧t; 106)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>licentiatus</ets>,
fr. <ets>licentiare</ets> to allow to do anything, fr. L.
<ets>licentia</ets> license. See <er>License</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who has a license to exercise a profession; <as>as,
a <ex>licentiate</ex> in medicine or theology</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The college of physicians, in July, 1687, published an edict,
requiring all the fellows, candidates, and <qex>licentiates</qex>, to
give gratuitous advice to the neighboring poor.</q>
<rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A friar authorized to receive confessions and grant
absolution in all places, independently of the local clergy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who acts without restraint, or takes a liberty,
as if having a license therefor.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>On the continent of Europe, a university degree
intermediate between that of bachelor and that of doctor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Licentiate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Licentiate
<hw>Li*cen"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(-sh⟦icr⟧*⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<def>To give a license to.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Licentious</ent>⟦br⟧
